div.p: V70/6999, unit 467, VPRS 3991/P inward registered correspondence, VA 475 Chief Secretary's Department, Public Record Office, Victoria.
MS written by Georg Luehmann, amended, signed and addressed by M. Melbourne Botanic Garden

In accordance with your instructions I have now the honor to transmit the returns required by Parliament in reference to the expenditure of the Botanic Garden during my administration, and the records of the property accumulated during my directorship.
W. Odgers to M, 27 May 1870 (in this edition as 70-05-27c) forwarded the questions to be answered for Parliament, listed in notes to Odger's letter.
M's letter was accompanied by the Return that follows; the file cover has a note by the Under Secretary, W. Odgers: 'Return sent to Clerk L. Assembly 7.7.70'. The file includes a separate page in M's hand that was evidently intended to serve as the heading for the Return: 'Return of the expenditure of the botanic Garden and the scientific institutions connected therewith from 1857 til June 1870, also of the present property of the establishment. (Correspondence)'.[Note that the Return referred only to the Gardens; M has added the rest, presumably as a reminder that the fund for which he was responsible were not only for the Gardens.]The return was presented to Parliament on 7 July 1870, when it was ordered to be laid upon the Table. ( Victoria
Votes and
p roceeding s of the Legislative Assembly
, session 1870, vol .1,
p. 161).
The Return itself , accompanied b a copy of M's letter,
is now located at
No. 249, unit 304, VPRS 3253/P Original papers tabled in the Legislative Assembly,
VA number , Public Record Office, Victoria.

After a careful valuation the property of the Botanic Garden, inclusive of the value of the plants distributed to Public and Government Institutions or for industrial purposes, from 1857 till 1870 amounts to £98,287 — s d whereas the expenditure, exclusive of special zoological disbursements and the cost of the Yarra bridges, has been £92,903.17/—

The lasting information afforded and numberless services rendered by the establishment under my charge since that time must be regarded as an additional and gratuitous boon of the Government to the community here and to countries abroad.
I have the honor to be,
